properties.abstract:
«The fact that William Tell was one from Uri, pleases old and young in this country.» Not so long ago, namely in 1970, this was written in the hiking guide for the canton of Uri. Therefore we begin at Tellsplatte, where William Tell supposedly, according to the legend and Friedrich Schiller’s play, escaped from Gessler’s boat. We ascend for a long time and increasingly steeply to the sky above Uri, until we cannot go any higher.
At Rophaien we get a sense of the freedom that seemed to have been so important for the folk hero and enjoy the breath-taking view down to the landscape the way it is 700 years later. Then we follow an exposed path across ridges so wild one could think they were battered by the oldest Uri phenomenon itself. No, not Tell but the Föhn (strong wind coming down from the mountains, which is called „the oldest Urner“).

sac_photos.title: On the ridge towards Äbneter Stöckli
Äbneter Stöckli and Rophaien, viewed from Diepen
The descent from Rophaien to Roten Chöpf is exposed, but equipped with steel cables.

segments.description: From the summit station of the aerial cable way Flüelen/Gruonbach–Ober Axen (ca. 980 m) hike to the mountain restaurant Ober Axen and around a clearing to Ober Frimseli (1170 m). The trail zigzags up to ca. 1200 m, passing Ober Frimseli on the south-east, and then turns right to P. 1399. Now hike on a faint, hardly visible path up to ca. 1650 m, where the path turns right. Above a rocky outcrop, at a simple emergency shelter at about 1720 m, the trail turns left continuing steeply, occasionally slightly exposed in grassy slopes to reach the saddle at ca. 1870 m between Blutt Stöckli and Rophaien. The rest of the 200 m is unproblematic. On the north-west ridge the trail leads to the large summit cross on Rophaien (2077 m).

photos.caption: From Ober Axen (down to the right) the trail goes steeply up the wild hay meadows to Rophaien.
The summit cross high above Lake Lucerne

segments.title: Ober Axen – Rophaien

segments.description: An exposed path links Rophaien with Äbneter Stöckli (2087 m). Normally you follow exactly the ridge line using your hands every once in a while, to keep your balance (especially where the trail has collapsed). At first descend a few metres from Rophaien (steel cables helping), then hike through the beautiful landscape around Roten Chöpf, and again with the help of steel cables, but not exposed, ascend to Äbneter Stöckli.

photos.caption: Across Roten Chöpf the trail goes towards Äbneter Stöckli.
The descent from Rophaien to Roten Chöpf is exposed, but equipped with steel cables.

segments.title: Rophaien - Äbneter Stöckli

segments.description:
After Äbneter Stöckli and Diepen keep left to reach Firtiggrätli (1959 m) and then descend to Rotenbalm. On the marked trail from Rotenbalm via Zingeli to the Gitschen summit station (1717 m) of the aerial cable way. Continue above the building to reach Lidernenhütte in about 10 minutes.
Variant: at ca. 1760 m traverse to the right to the face in order to go around the outcrop of a mountain top on the north, keeping the altitude (one passage with steel cables). Shortly afterwards you stand before the Gitschen station.

photos.caption: After Rotenbalm the terrain gets more and more rocky. View back to Diepen

segments.title: Äbneter Stöckli - Rotenbalm - Zingeli -  Lidernenhütte
